WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.460
this isn't a novel therapy. It's more of a predictive and prognostic thing that we're

00:00:03.460 --> 00:00:08.060
looking at that might be explaining why some patients have a deep response in both CAR-T

00:00:08.060 --> 00:00:13.340
therapy and bispecific therapy. So we all know we've had fantastic responses still to cell

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:17.820
patients having what could be considered a cure now with five years of aggression-free survival

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:23.760
or greater, but there are still patients that do not have that response. And we did a deep dive to

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:26.780
see what was causing that. And we published a paper and other individuals said it too,

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:30.800
that at month one, there might be myeloid suppression that's in preventing this long

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:34.860
durable response in patients. So if you see here in the red, at month one, there's an expansion

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:38.800
of these myeloid-derived suppressor cells that is present in patients that do not have a PFS

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:43.060
of greater than five years. And when we looked at the gene expression profile of those myeloid,

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:50.800
of MDSCs, we found that they were, we found that they were enriched for S100A8 and A9 gene

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:56.460
expression. And S100A8 and A9 is a calprotectin. It's a damage-associated molecular protein.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:01:00.740
It's produced by myeloid cells, stromal cells, and mesenchyne cells. And it acts as an alarmin.

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:06.460
It promotes more MDSCs and actually expansion of T-regulatory T-cells, T-regulatory cells,

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:10.560
and in general creates an immunosuppressive microenvironment. And this has been known

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:14.920
to be elevated in blood cancer, such as myeloma, and it's associated with negative prognosis.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:19.200
So we wanted to validate this in our patients. So we took a separate cohort of patients. We took

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:23.540
four patients that had rapid progression or median PFS of less than nine days and compared

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:26.520
those to had a durable response. And we looked at soluble,

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:30.520
S100 levels in the peripheral blood. And we can see at month one, we have the rapid

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:34.880
regression is having a significantly higher presence of this S100A8, A9. And when we looked

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:39.520
at the immune microenvironment, they actually also had higher T-regs, higher MDSCs. And more

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:43.340
importantly, we couldn't find circulating CAR-T. So there's truncated CAR-T expansion in these

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:48.440
patients. We thought, is this specific to CAR-T or is this for all T-cell-directed therapies?

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:53.400
We moved to look at this in our bispecific treated patients. So we took a cohort of 19 patients here

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:56.220
and we looked at S100 levels at baseline.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:01.860
And during therapy, what we can see is that the patients who did not achieve, who had greater than

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:07.800
a VGPR had significantly lower S100 levels in the blood at both baseline and then during

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:12.200
bispecific therapy around cycle three, day one. So patients who had a deep response had significantly

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:17.240
lower S100. When we looked at it in terms of progression-free survival, we looked at the

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:21.820
median between those who had high and less high and low S100. We found that the patients who had

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:25.920
higher S100 had significantly lower progression-free survival. And in general,

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:32.480
the levels of S100 in the peripheral blood correlated negatively with PFS. So more S100,

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:37.440
less progression-free survival in our patients. So we wanted to see, did that affect the T-cells

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:42.180
of our patients who have a short PFS? So we did a immunophenotyping and looked to see,

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:45.660
are there any changes within the T-cell microenvironment in these patients?

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:49.500
First thing we looked at was TOCS, which is a transcriptional factor that's known to be in

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:55.620
exhausted cells and does drive general exhaustion markers at PD1 and CD39. And we found that the

00:02:55.620 --> 00:03:01.320
short PFS in general had higher presence of these CD3 TOCS cells. When we used spatial

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:05.860
transpectomics, we actually found that the myeloid cells that had S100 co-localized with

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:09.740
exhausted T-cells. So in the corner in the yellow, you see these blue myeloid cells that

00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:14.520
are S100 negative, and they're co-localizing to T-cells that are also TOCS negative. While in the

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:19.200
red, you see the yellow myeloid cells that express S100, and they co-localize to these

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:23.980
purple TOCS positive T-cells, indicating that there is enrichment of these myeloid cells to

00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:25.320
exhausted T-cells.

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:30.360
And when we do correlations again, we see that in general, progression-free survival

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:34.900
negatively correlates with TOCS presence. So less progression-free survival with more of

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:39.820
these cells that have higher TOCS, and S100 correlated significantly with the amount of

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:43.680
TOCS cells. Now we wanted to make sure, because there's a lot of debate of what is an exhausted

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:47.000
cell, we want to make sure that this TOCS expression correlated with actual functionality.

00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:51.260
So we took our patient cells, we actually co-cultured them with myeloma cells and

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:55.020
teclistamab, and we wanted to see, does this lead to reduced cytotoxicity?

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:59.440
And what we ended up seeing is that just like in the TOCS presence, the patients who had short

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:05.460
PFS actually had significantly lower cytotoxicity in our in vitro culture. And like we saw before,

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.400
this correlated actually with the amount of TOCS cells and the amount of S100. So you had less

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:15.700
cytotoxicity with the more presence of these TOCS positive cells, and you had less cytotoxicity with

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:20.080
the amount of S100 that was there. So we wanted to validate this in vitro.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:23.840
We wanted to make sure that this is a direct effect and not just a correlation. So we took

00:04:23.840 --> 00:04:24.600
healthy donor,

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:32.060
PBMCs, and then derived CAR-Ts from them and incubated them 72 hours with S100. And then we

00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:36.420
captured dynamic changes. In the interest of time, I'm not going to show it, but they did increase in

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:40.520
TOCS levels and they actually did differentiate more into T regulatory cells. But functionally,

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:46.780
on the top here, you see that cytotoxicity and both CAR-T cytotoxicity were dose-dependently

00:04:46.780 --> 00:04:50.220
inhibited by the amount of S100 that we cultured them for time.

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:54.420
So the more S100 that we added to the media, the less cytotoxicity the cells

00:04:54.420 --> 00:05:00.840
were in vitro. So what we end up getting is a system where you have this immunosuppressive

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:08.080
ligand that's attaching, influencing CAR-T cells and T cells and making them not able to attack

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:14.420
the myeloma cell. So in conjunction with Albert Einstein Medicine and Amit Verna and

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:18.460
Roshan Therapeutics, they actually formulated a monoclonal antibody that blocks the binding of

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:24.120
S100 to all of its receptors. And we tested this in vitro in our ongoing studies in vivo to see if

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:28.620
this does actually recapitulate the response that we had and prevent T cell dysfunction.

00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:33.280
So this is some of the results that we have from there. On the left, you have healthy derived CAR-T

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:37.700
cells that were incubated, again, 72 hours with S100. And on the right, you have peripheral blood

00:05:37.700 --> 00:05:42.600
mononuclear cells that were incubated 72 hours. And then in the blue is with nothing added. In

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:47.260
the red, you have the inhibitory effect that we're mentioning S100 has on the T cells and CAR-T cells.

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:52.600
And then strikingly, the pink is the salvage that's done when you add the monoclonal antibody to prevent

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:53.820
this T cell exhaustion. And then on the right, you have the monoclonal antibody that was incubated

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:58.540
to prevent this T cell exhaustion. And again, I'm not including a lot of this, but you do see a lot of

00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:03.440
less differentiation of T cells when you add this monoclonal, less differentiation of T regulatory

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:06.940
cells when you add this monoclonal antibody. In the immune microbiome, you also have less

00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:11.220
differentiation of myeloid derived suppressor cells. So you, in general, you have a less

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:16.220
immunosuppressive microenvironment. So with this, I just want to conclude by saying that we are

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:22.180
seeing that S100-88 and A9 does predict inferior depth of response in patients, especially those

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:23.520
who are receiving T cell-directed therapy. And we're seeing that S100-88 does predict inferior depth of

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:25.180
response in patients, especially those who are receiving T cell-directed therapy. It promotes the

00:06:25.180 --> 00:06:29.560
increase of tox, reduced cytokine production, which I don't show here, but it did have a universal

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:34.160
decrease of cytokine, antigen-specific cytokine production, and cytotoxicity. And when you

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:38.780
neutralize it using a monoclonal antibody, you can actually salvage this T cell dysfunction,

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:44.420
making it a strong therapeutic target for not just multiple myeloma, but all T cell-directed therapy.

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:47.640
And with that, I want to thank everyone for all that.
